revision.text:
'''2000, Seen By...''' ({{lang-fr|'''2000 vu par...'''}}) was a 1998 international film project initiated by the French company Haut et Court to produce films depicting the approaching turn of the millennium seen from the perspectives of 10 different countries.<ref name="Allon">Yoram Allon, Del Cullen, Hannah Patterson, ''Contemporary North American Film Directors: A Wallflower Critical Guide'', Wallflower Press, 2002, p. 367.</ref>
The idea was conceived by producers Caroline Benjo and Carole Scotta, who took the idea to Pierre Chevalier of the French-German TV station [[Arte]]. They envisioned each film to be one hour long, made for the cost of four to five million francs, by promising directors.<ref name="O'Shaughnessy">Martin O'Shaughnessy, ''Laurent Cantet'', Oxford University Press, p. 4.</ref>
Ten films were produced as a result of the project:
