{{Culture of the United States}}
The literature of [[Alabama]], [[United States]], includes fiction, poetry, and nonfiction. Representative authors include [[Fannie Flagg]] and [[Harper Lee]].{{sfn|Hitchcock|2001}}

==History==
{{Expand section|date=March 2017 }}
[[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]-born [[Augusta Jane Evans]] (1835-1909) moved to [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]] in 1849 and wrote many popular novels that incorporated aspects of her experience in Alabama.<ref>{{cite book |editor=[[Emory Elliott]] |title= Columbia History of the American Novel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2IA7o-OTyEsC|year= 1991 |publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=978-0-231-07360-8 }}</ref>

In 1960, Harper Lee, born in Monroeville, published perhaps the most celebrated novel set in Alabama, ''[[To Kill A Mockingbird]]''.

==Awards and events==
The Alabama Library Association launched its "Alabama Author Awards" in 1957 for fiction, nonfiction and poetry; honorees have included [[Gail Godwin]], [[Ann Waldron]], [[Kathryn Tucker Windham]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.allanet.org/?page=74 |title=Alabama Author Awards |author=Authors Awards Committee |publisher=Alabama Library Association |accessdate= March 11, 2017 }} (List of winners)</ref> The Alabama Writers' Forum began in 1992.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.writersforum.org/about/writers_forum.html |title= About |publisher=Alabama Writers' Forum |accessdate= March 11, 2017 |location= Montgomery, AL }}</ref>

