{{Orphan|date=June 2013}} {{Infobox website | name = ''CollegeTimes'' | url = [https://collegetimes.co collegetimes.co] | commercial = Yes | type = [[Analytic journalism]] | language = [[English language|English]] | launch_date = November 17, 2008 | current_status = Online }}
'''CollegeTimes''' is a [[life hacking]] [[blog]] focused on "real world education" that features an online database of more than 15,000 colleges and universities and their accompanying "uncensored" student reviews, which claims to be the largest higher education directory on the [[Internet]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://collegetimes.co/about/ | title=About CollegeTimes | publisher=''CollegeTimes'' | accessdate=2015-06-30}}</ref> The website has created controversy among multiple for-profit college institutions in the [[United States]] and [[Canada]] because of negative student reviews (user-generated) that appear on certain school profiles, which has led to ongoing legal threats and outcries being aimed at '''CollegeTimes''' and their various business partners.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2015/04/10/reports-troubles-webster-u%E2%80%99s-branch-campus-thailand | title=Reports of troubles at Webster U's branch campus in Thailand | publisher=''[[Inside Higher Ed]]'' | accessdate=2015-06-30}}</ref>
The website's managed WordPress hosting provider [[LittleBizzy]] was sued in the United States in 2012 by [[Neumont University]], a for-profit technical institute based in Utah, after being accused of "business disparagement" that allegedly cost the college more than $1 million in lost revenue due to negative student reviews appearing on '''CollegeTimes'''.<ref>http://blog.ericgoldman.org/archives/2014/05/college-review-website-ordered-to-pay-1m-for-users-disparaging-reviews-neumont-university-v-little-bizzy.htm</ref> However, the case was eventually thrown out due to improper service of process.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://collegetimes.co/neumont-university-gives-up-lawsuit/ | title= Utah’s For-Profit Neumont ‘University’ Gives Up Fight Against CollegeTimes After Expensive 2-Year Battle | publisher=''CollegeTimes'' | accessdate=2015-06-30}}</ref>
The case garnered attention across the Ninth [[Circuit Court]] after the magistrate judge initially assigned to the case refused to admit [[Section 230 of the Communications Decency Act|Section 230]] arguments - which protect web hosting companies in regard to free speech issues - into the case; the judge went so far as to completely strike LittleBizzy's mention of Section 230 protections from the public record for unexplained reasons,<ref>http://pubcit.typepad.com/clpblog/2014/05/nevada-trial-judge-limits-default-judgment-against-host-of-critical-comments-was-the-relief-awarded-.html</ref> leading '''CollegeTimes''' to accuse the two judges involved in the case of favoring Neumont due to an alleged common affiliation with [[Mormonism]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://collegetimes.co/neumont-university-gives-up-lawsuit/ | title= Utah’s For-Profit Neumont ‘University’ Gives Up Fight Against CollegeTimes After Expensive 2-Year Battle | publisher=''CollegeTimes'' | accessdate=2015-06-30}}</ref>
