{{refimprove|date=August 2017}} {{Anime and manga}}
{{nihongo|'''[[Dōjinshi|Dōjin]] soft'''|同人ソフト}}, also sometimes called {{nihongo|'''dōjin games'''|同人ゲーム}}, with '''dōjin''' sometimes transliterated as ''doujin'' or ''doujinshi'', are [[video game]]s created by [[Japan]]ese [[Fan-made|hobbyists]] or hobbyist groups (referred to as "[[dōjin circle|circles]]"), more for fun than for profit; essentially, the [[Japan]]ese equivalent of [[Independent video game development|independent video games]] or [[Fangame]]s. Most of them are based on pre-existing material ("[[Video game mod|modding]]"), but some are entirely original creations. They are almost always exclusive to [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]]-based [[Personal computer|PC]]s, but a few notable exceptions also exist for the [[Dreamcast]], a console on which [[Homebrew (video games)|homebrew]] development was popular.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}
Dōjin soft are typically available in "demo" or "trial" (体験版 ''taikenban'') form [[Freeware|for free]] on the internet, with full versions available for purchase. One game, [[French-Bread]]'s [[beat em up|brawler]] ''[[Ragnarok Battle Offline]]'', a [[Homage (arts)|homage]]/[[Parody|spoof]] of the [[MMORPG]] ''[[Ragnarok Online]]'' so impressed [[Gravity Corp.]] (the original game's designers) that it has been given an official release outside Japan.
Like [[fangames]], dōjin soft frequently use characters from existing games, [[anime]], or [[manga]]. These unauthorized uses of characters are generally ignored and accepted by the copyright holders, and are seen as encouraging a greater fan community. There are also many dōjin soft titles which are completely original, or feature only vague allusions to other series.
While most dōjin soft sales occur at anime and video game or [[List of anime conventions|anime conventions]] (such as [[Comiket]]), there is a growing number of specialized [[internet]] sites that sell them. Some titles sell well enough that their creators can make a full-time job out of their "amateur hobby". One particular circle, [[TYPE-MOON]], has since become a commercial videogame developer.
Dōjin soft games typically do not get released outside Japan due to language barriers. Recently, independent Western developers have offered to help translate these games for release in other markets, with one of the first known successful examples being ''[[Recettear: An Item Shop's Tale]]'', developed originally by [[EasyGameStation]] in 2007, and then localized and released by [[Carpe Fulgur]] in 2010 for English audiences, which had a modest success with over 300,000 units sold in these markets.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/32250/Carpe_Fulghur_Talks_Sales_Reality_As_Promos_Lead_Recettear_Over_100000_Units.php | title = Carpe Fulghur Talks Sales Reality As Promos Lead Recettear Over 100,000 Units | first = Leigh | last = Alexander | date = 2011-01-03 | accessdate = 2011-01-03 | publisher = [[Gamasutra]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url =https://arstechnica.com/gaming/news/2010/12/low-prices-low-expectations-ars-looks-at-indie-game-pricing.ars | title = Low prices, low expectations? Ars looks at indie game pricing | first = Andrew | last = Webster | date = 2010-12-21 | accessdate= 2011-01-04 | publisher = [[Ars Technica]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2011/01/17/post-mortem-recettear/ | title = Post Mortem: Recettear | first = Alec | last = Meer | date = 2011-01-17 | accessdate = 2011-01-17 | publisher = [[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]] }}</ref> This approach has been used to bring other dōjin soft games, particularly visual novels and dating sims, to the West.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://gamasutra.com/blogs/CelsoRiva/20150713/248338/Making_and_selling_visual_novels_and_dating_sims.php | title = Making and selling visual novels and dating sims | first = Celso | last = Riva | date = July 13, 2015 | accessdate = November 11, 2015 | work = [[Gamasutra]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/06/06/date-a-pigeon-in-hatoful-boyfriend | title = Hatoful Boyfriend Coming to US This Summer | date = June 6, 2014 | first = Miranda | last = Sanchez | work = [[IGN]] }}</ref>
==Notable dōjin soft companies== *[[07th Expansion]]: specializes in [[visual novel]]s, most notable for ''[[Higurashi no Naku Koro ni]]'' and ''[[Umineko no Naku Koro ni]]''. *[[ABA Games]]: specializes in [[shoot 'em up]]s with an abstract look. Most of their games are [[open source]]. *[[EasyGameStation]]: produces a wide variety of games, from [[brawler]]s to [[role playing game]]s to [[strategy games]], most notably released ''[[Recettear: An Item Shop's Tale]]'', the first dōjin soft to be distributed on the [[Steam (software)|Steam]] platform overseas to great success. *[[erka:es]]: specializes in [[platformer]]s, most notable for ''[[Rosenkreuzstilette]]'', a [[Video game clone|clone]] of ''[[Mega Man]]'' with magic and German horror themes.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}} *[[Team Shanghai Alice]]: specializes in [[Bullet hell|curtain fire]] [[Scrolling shooters|scrolling shooter]]s, most notable for the [[Touhou Project]]. *[[Twilight Frontier]]: specializes in a wide variety of games including [[fighting game]]s and [[platformer]]s. *[[Type-Moon]]: former dōjin studio that specializes in [[visual novel]]s.
